## Step 2
The event $A_i$ denotes a match on the $i$th draw. The probability of a match on the $i$th draw can be calculated by considering the total number of ways to arrange $n$ balls and the number of arrangements where the $i$th ball is in the $i$th position.

## Step 3
For a specific $i$, the probability of $A_i$ happening is $\frac{(n-1)!}{n!} = \frac{1}{n}$ because there are $(n-1)!$ ways to arrange the remaining $n-1$ balls after fixing the $i$th ball in its correct position, out of $n!$ total arrangements.

## Step 4
To find the probability of at least one match, we can use the principle of inclusion-exclusion. The probability of at least one match is $P(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup ... \cup A_n)$.

## Step 5
Using the principle of inclusion-exclusion, $P(A_1 \cup A_2 \cup ... \cup A_n) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} P(A_i) - \sum_{i<j} P(A_i \cap A_j) + \sum_{i<j<k} P(A_i \cap A_j \cap A_k) - ... + (-1)^{n+1}P(A_1 \cap A_2 \cap ... \cap A_n)$.

